# Detailed SEO Implementation Plan for iskrib_v3

## Executive Summary

This plan addresses five critical SEO gaps in the iskrib_v3 webapp, ordered by impact and implementability. The architecture constraint is that the **client is a static site on Render.com** (no server middleware possible) while the **Express server is a separate service** that CAN serve dynamic content. All changes are additive -- nothing existing breaks.

---

## Phase 1: Dynamic Sitemap Endpoints (HIGHEST IMPACT, LOWEST RISK)

### Why this matters most
Google cannot index what it cannot discover. Right now the sitemap at `https://iskrib.com/sitemap.xml` only lists 6 static pages. Every post and every user profile is invisible to Google's crawlers. A dynamic sitemap is the single most impactful change for discoverability.

### 1A. Create `GET /api/sitemap-posts.xml` on the Express server

**File to create:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\server\routes\sitemapRoutes.js`

**Approach:**
- Create a new Express Router module dedicated to sitemap endpoints
- Query Supabase for all public journals: `SELECT id, title, created_at, updated_at FROM journals WHERE privacy = 'public' ORDER BY created_at DESC`
- Reuse the `makePostUrl` function already in `server/server.js` (line 42-47) to generate canonical post URLs with slugs
- Generate valid XML sitemap with `<url>`, `<loc>`, `<lastmod>`, `<changefreq>`, `<priority>` elements
- Set `Cache-Control: public, max-age=3600` (1 hour) to avoid hammering Supabase
- Set `Content-Type: application/xml`

**Key implementation detail -- extracting `makePostUrl`:** The `makePostUrl` function at line 42 of `server/server.js` is currently a local function. It should be extracted into a shared utility file (`server/utils/urlUtils.js`) so it can be used by both the share routes in server.js and the new sitemap routes.

```javascript
// server/routes/sitemapRoutes.js (conceptual)
import express from 'express';
import supabase from '../services/supabase.js';
import { makePostUrl } from '../utils/urlUtils.js';

const sitemapRouter = express.Router();
const SITEMAP_CACHE_SECONDS = 3600;

sitemapRouter.get('/sitemap-posts.xml', async (req, res) => {
    try {
        const { data: journals, error } = await supabase
            .from('journals')
            .select('id, title, created_at')
            .eq('privacy', 'public')
            .order('created_at', { ascending: false })
            .limit(50000); // Sitemap protocol max

        if (error) throw error;

        const urls = (journals || []).map(j => {
            const loc = makePostUrl(j.id, j.title || '');
            const lastmod = (j.created_at || new Date().toISOString()).slice(0, 10);
            return `  <url>\n    <loc>${escapeXml(loc)}</loc>\n    <lastmod>${lastmod}</lastmod>\n    <changefreq>monthly</changefreq>\n    <priority>0.6</priority>\n  </url>`;
        }).join('\n');

        const xml = `<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n<urlset xmlns="http://www.sitemaps.org/schemas/sitemap/0.9">\n${urls}\n</urlset>`;

        res.set('Content-Type', 'application/xml');
        res.set('Cache-Control', `public, max-age=${SITEMAP_CACHE_SECONDS}`);
        res.send(xml);
    } catch (err) {
        console.error('sitemap-posts error:', err?.message || err);
        res.status(500).set('Content-Type', 'text/plain').send('error generating sitemap');
    }
});
```

**Risk level:** Very low. This is a new GET endpoint that reads from Supabase -- zero impact on existing functionality.

### 1B. Create `GET /api/sitemap-profiles.xml` on the Express server

**Same file:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\server\routes\sitemapRoutes.js`

**Approach:**
- Query: `SELECT id, name, created_at FROM users ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 50000`
- Generate URLs in the format `https://iskrib.com/user/{userId}` (using the new clean URL path from Phase 3)
- For now, ALSO include the current format `https://iskrib.com/visitProfile?userId={uuid}` to match what actually works
- Once Phase 3 lands the new `/user/:userId` route, switch to that

**Risk level:** Very low. Same reasoning as 1A.

### 1C. Create `GET /api/sitemap-index.xml` on the Express server

**Same file:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\server\routes\sitemapRoutes.js`

**Approach:**
- A sitemap index that references:
  1. `https://iskrib.com/sitemap.xml` (the static sitemap, already exists at build time)
  2. `https://iskrib.com/api/sitemap-posts.xml` (the dynamic posts sitemap, served by Express)
  3. `https://iskrib.com/api/sitemap-profiles.xml` (the dynamic profiles sitemap, served by Express)

```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<sitemapindex xmlns="http://www.sitemaps.org/schemas/sitemap/0.9">
  <sitemap>
    <loc>https://iskrib.com/sitemap.xml</loc>
  </sitemap>
  <sitemap>
    <loc>https://iskrib.com/api/sitemap-posts.xml</loc>
  </sitemap>
  <sitemap>
    <loc>https://iskrib.com/api/sitemap-profiles.xml</loc>
  </sitemap>
</sitemapindex>
```

### 1D. Wire sitemap routes into server.js

**File to modify:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\server\server.js`

Add one line:
```javascript
import sitemapRouter from './routes/sitemapRoutes.js';
// ...existing middleware...
app.use('/api', sitemapRouter);
```

This should be placed BEFORE the existing `app.use('/api', router);` line (line 600) to ensure it gets matched.

### 1E. Update `robots.txt` to reference the sitemap index

**File to modify:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\public\robots.txt`

Change from:
```
Sitemap: https://iskrib.com/sitemap.xml
```
To:
```
User-agent: *
Allow: /

Disallow: /profile
Disallow: /home/bookmark
Disallow: /home/collections
Disallow: /home/notifications
Disallow: /home/contentViewer

Sitemap: https://iskrib.com/api/sitemap-index.xml
```

The `Disallow` lines save crawl budget by telling Google not to index authenticated-only pages. The sitemap index URL points to the server-rendered index.

**Risk level:** Very low. Robots.txt changes are advisory only and the disallowed paths are auth-only pages that would have no useful content for crawlers anyway.

### 1F. Extract `makePostUrl` to shared utility

**File to create:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\server\utils\urlUtils.js`

Extract from server.js lines 12-47 the constants (`SITE_URL`) and `makePostUrl` function so they can be imported by both `server.js` and `sitemapRoutes.js`.

**File to modify:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\server\server.js` -- import `makePostUrl` and `SITE_URL` from the new utility instead of defining them locally.

---

## Phase 2: Enhanced SeoManager for Post Pages (HIGH IMPACT, MODERATE EFFORT)

### Why this matters
When Googlebot renders a post page (e.g., `/home/post/abc-123/my-great-post`), it currently sees the generic title "Iskryb Post" and description "Read community journals and discussions on Iskryb." Every post looks identical in search results. With proper meta tags, each post becomes a unique, clickable search result.

### 2A. Create a `usePostSeo` hook

**File to create:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\seo\usePostSeo.js`

**Approach:**
- This hook watches for when post data is loaded in ContentView
- It calls functions on SeoManager to update meta tags dynamically
- It restores default SEO when unmounting

```javascript
// Conceptual shape
import { useEffect } from 'react';
import { SITE_NAME, SITE_URL, buildAbsoluteUrl } from './seoConfig.js';

const truncate = (text, maxLen = 160) => {
    if (!text || text.length <= maxLen) return text || '';
    return text.slice(0, maxLen - 3).trimEnd() + '...';
};

const usePostSeo = (postData) => {
    useEffect(() => {
        if (!postData?.title) return;

        const title = `${postData.title} | ${SITE_NAME}`;
        const description = truncate(postData.wholeText) 
            || `Read "${postData.title}" by ${postData.name || 'someone'} on ${SITE_NAME}`;
        const canonicalUrl = `${SITE_URL}/home/post/${postData.journalId}`;

        // Update document.title
        document.title = title;

        // Update meta tags using the same ensureMeta pattern from SeoManager
        updateMeta('seo-description', 'name', 'description', description);
        updateMeta('seo-og-type', 'property', 'og:type', 'article');
        updateMeta('seo-og-title', 'property', 'og:title', title);
        updateMeta('seo-og-description', 'property', 'og:description', description);
        updateMeta('seo-og-url', 'property', 'og:url', canonicalUrl);
        // ... twitter tags ...

        // Add Article JSON-LD
        updateJsonLd('seo-ld-article', {
            "@context": "https://schema.org",
            "@type": "Article",
            "headline": postData.title,
            "description": description,
            "datePublished": postData.created_at,
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": postData.name || "Anonymous"
            },
            "publisher": {
                "@type": "Organization",
                "name": SITE_NAME,
                "url": SITE_URL
            },
            "mainEntityOfPage": canonicalUrl
        });

        return () => {
            // Cleanup: remove article JSON-LD, SeoManager will restore defaults on next route change
            removeElement('seo-ld-article');
        };
    }, [postData?.journalId, postData?.title, postData?.wholeText, postData?.name, postData?.created_at]);
};
```

**Key design decision:** The `ensureMeta`, `ensureJsonLd`, and `removeElementById` helper functions are currently defined inside `SeoManager.jsx` as local functions. They should be extracted into a shared `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\seo\seoUtils.js` module so both SeoManager and usePostSeo can use them.

### 2B. Extract DOM helpers from SeoManager

**File to create:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\seo\seoUtils.js`

Extract `ensureMeta`, `removeElementById`, `ensureLink`, and `ensureJsonLd` from `SeoManager.jsx` (lines 13-57) into this shared module.

**File to modify:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\seo\SeoManager.jsx` -- import the helpers from `seoUtils.js` instead of defining them locally.

### 2C. Integrate `usePostSeo` into ContentView

**File to modify:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\components\HomePage\ContentViewer\ContentView.jsx`

- Import `usePostSeo`
- Call `usePostSeo(postData)` inside the ContentView component, right after the `postData` useMemo (around line 170)
- Remove the existing manual `document.title` effect at lines 302-310 (usePostSeo subsumes it)

This is safe because:
- ContentView already computes `postData` with title, wholeText, name, created_at, journalId
- The hook only runs when postData is available
- On unmount, it cleans up

**Risk level:** Low. The only behavioral change is better meta tags when viewing a post. The existing SeoManager continues to handle all other routes unchanged.

### 2D. Update `DYNAMIC_PATTERNS` in seoConfig.js to set canonicalPath

**File to modify:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\seo\seoConfig.js`

The existing dynamic pattern at lines 95-105 sets `canonicalPath: null`. This should be changed to generate a proper canonical from the pathname:

```javascript
const DYNAMIC_PATTERNS = [
    {
        test: (pathname) => /^\/home\/post\/[^/]+(?:\/[^/]+)?$/.test(pathname),
        seo: (pathname) => {
            // Extract journalId from pathname for canonical (strip slug for canonical consistency)
            const match = pathname.match(/^\/home\/post\/([^/]+)/);
            const journalId = match ? match[1] : '';
            return {
                title: `${SITE_NAME} Post`,
                description: "Read community journals and discussions on Iskryb.",
                canonicalPath: `/home/post/${journalId}`,
                robots: "index,follow",
            };
        },
    },
];
```

Note: This requires a small change to `getSeoForPath` to support function-based seo values:

```javascript
export const getSeoForPath = (pathname) => {
    const normalized = pathname || "/";
    const exactMatch = SEO_ROUTES.find((route) => route.path === normalized);
    if (exactMatch) return { ...DEFAULT_SEO, ...exactMatch };

    const dynamicMatch = DYNAMIC_PATTERNS.find((entry) => entry.test(normalized));
    if (dynamicMatch) {
        const seoData = typeof dynamicMatch.seo === 'function' 
            ? dynamicMatch.seo(normalized) 
            : dynamicMatch.seo;
        return { ...DEFAULT_SEO, ...seoData };
    }

    return { ...DEFAULT_SEO };
};
```

**Risk level:** Low. This only changes how the canonical URL is computed for post pages, and it's a strictly better canonical (includes journalId, strips slug for consistency).

---

## Phase 3: Profile URL Restructuring (MEDIUM IMPACT, MODERATE RISK)

### Why this matters
Current profile URLs are `https://iskrib.com/visitProfile?userId=7ceaa0ad-0266-...` -- these are difficult for Google to crawl and look terrible in search results. Clean URLs like `/user/7ceaa0ad-...` are much better for SEO and shareability.

### 3A. Add new route `/user/:userId` in App.jsx

**File to modify:** `C:\Users\johnm\iskrib_v3\client\src\App.jsx`

Add a NEW route alongside the existing one (both continue to work):

```jsx
